1
00:00:37,594 --> 00:00:41,597
[MUSIC CHATTER
PLAYING ON RADIO]

2
00:00:50,567 --> 00:00:54,570
MAN 1 [ON RADIO]:
- Clearly, I've never been there, but...

3
00:00:56,573 --> 00:01:00,658
MAN 2:usually the situation,
obviously a major malfunction.

4
00:01:00,826 --> 00:01:03,579
[PEOPLE CHATTERING
IN FOREIGN LANGUAGES ON RADIO]

5
00:01:14,882 --> 00:01:17,134
MAN 3:
- Whether or not their president is a crook.

6
00:01:17,301 --> 00:01:18,593
MAN 4:
Well, I'm not a crook.

7
00:01:18,760 --> 00:01:22,597
MAN 5:
- Small step for man, one giant leap for...

8
00:01:22,763 --> 00:01:26,933
MAN 6: Robert Kennedy was shot
in that ballroom.

9
00:01:28,436 --> 00:01:31,105
MAN 7:
Thank God almighty, we are free at last.

10
00:01:31,272 --> 00:01:33,900
MAN 8:
A sniper has fired at President Kennedy.

11
00:01:41,283 --> 00:01:42,616
MAN 9:
- The Communist party...

12
00:01:42,783 --> 00:01:45,036
...or have you ever been
a member of the Communist party?

13
00:01:45,204 --> 00:01:49,456
MAN 10:
Old soldiers never die. They just...

14
00:01:49,625 --> 00:01:52,210
MAN 11:
Hi-yo, Silver!

15
00:01:53,878 --> 00:01:56,713
MAN 12:
- Something never before experienced...

16
00:01:56,882 --> 00:02:01,302
MAN 13:
- 1941, a date which will live...

17
00:02:05,641 --> 00:02:10,019
MAN 14: And we continue this final edition
of our Maxwell House Good News of 1939.

18
00:02:10,187 --> 00:02:12,312
MAN 15: Good evening,
Mr. And Mrs. North America...

19
00:02:12,480 --> 00:02:14,856
...and all the ships at sea.
Let's go to press.

20
00:02:19,070 --> 00:02:23,490
[MUSIC AND CHATTER FADING]

21
00:03:32,393 --> 00:03:36,562
GIRL:
CQ, this is W-9 GFO.

22
00:03:38,064 --> 00:03:42,526
CQ, this is W-9 GFO here. Come back?

23
00:03:44,112 --> 00:03:45,530
CQ.

24
00:03:45,698 --> 00:03:50,200
CQ, this is W-9 GFO here.

25
00:03:50,368 --> 00:03:52,037
Come back?

26
00:03:52,579 --> 00:03:54,038
[KNOCKING]

27
00:03:54,206 --> 00:03:55,372
[DOOR OPENS]

28
00:03:55,540 --> 00:04:00,544
CQ, CQ, this is W-9 GFO.
Is anybody out there?

29
00:04:00,712 --> 00:04:02,004
Not getting anything.

30
00:04:02,173 --> 00:04:03,757
Small moves, Ellie.

31
00:04:05,217 --> 00:04:06,592
Small moves.

32
00:04:09,094 --> 00:04:13,598
CQ, this is W-9 GFO here. Come back?

33
00:04:13,766 --> 00:04:17,769
MAN:
Copy, W-9 GFO. K-4 WLD here.

34
00:04:17,937 --> 00:04:21,189
- What do I say?
- Just be yourself.

35
00:04:21,649 --> 00:04:25,860
- Where are you, K-4 WLD? Come back?
- Pensacola. Over.

36
00:04:26,028 --> 00:04:27,612
Pensacola, where's Pensacola?

37
00:04:27,781 --> 00:04:29,781
I'll give you a hint.

38
00:04:29,949 --> 00:04:31,240
Orange juice.

39
00:04:33,952 --> 00:04:37,790
Copy that, K-4 WLD.
How's the weather down there in Florida?

40
00:04:39,084 --> 00:04:41,334
TED:
Pensacola, Florida.

41
00:04:41,502 --> 00:04:44,170
I have to tell you, Sparks...

42
00:04:44,338 --> 00:04:47,841
...one thousand, one hundred
and sixteen miles.

43
00:04:48,009 --> 00:04:51,470
Pretty good. That's the farthest yet.

44
00:05:03,858 --> 00:05:07,151
ELLIE: Can we hear all the way to New York?
TED: Sure.

45
00:05:08,529 --> 00:05:12,490
ELLIE: Can we hear all the way to California?
TED: I don't see why not.

46
00:05:13,242 --> 00:05:16,954
ELLIE: Can we hear all the way to Alaska?
TED: Yeah, on a really clear day.

47
00:05:17,163 --> 00:05:19,665
ELLIE:
Can we hear all the way to China?

48
00:05:20,207 --> 00:05:22,250
TED:
On a really, really clear day.

49
00:05:22,418 --> 00:05:23,836
[CHUCKLING]

50
00:05:24,545 --> 00:05:27,172
ELLIE:
Could we talk to the moon?

51
00:05:27,339 --> 00:05:30,175
TED: Well, if it's a big enough radio,
I don't see why not.

52
00:05:30,843 --> 00:05:32,843
ELLIE:
Could we talk to Jupiter?

53
00:05:33,052 --> 00:05:35,846
Or what's the one after that?

54
00:05:36,014 --> 00:05:37,848
Don't tell me.

55
00:05:39,685 --> 00:05:41,351
TED:
I'll give you a hint.

56
00:05:41,519 --> 00:05:42,687
Hula-Hoops.

57
00:05:42,896 --> 00:05:46,189
- Saturn. Could we talk to Saturn?
- Mm-hm.

58
00:05:50,778 --> 00:05:53,781
Dad, could we talk to Mom?

59
00:05:58,870 --> 00:06:01,956
I don't think even the biggest radio
could reach that far.

60
00:06:07,086 --> 00:06:09,379
All right, no more stalling.

61
00:06:10,923 --> 00:06:12,382
Okay.

62
00:06:13,968 --> 00:06:15,343
Pensacola.

63
00:06:22,144 --> 00:06:24,478
Oh, Ellie, that's a beauty.

64
00:06:25,980 --> 00:06:27,731
Now get some sleep.

65
00:06:35,740 --> 00:06:37,783
- Hey, Dad?
- Yeah?

66
00:06:37,951 --> 00:06:40,745
Do you think there's people
on other planets?

67
00:06:40,913 --> 00:06:42,579
I don't know, Sparks.

68
00:06:44,081 --> 00:06:46,082
But I guess I'd say...

69
00:06:46,250 --> 00:06:48,418
...if it is just us...

70
00:06:49,588 --> 00:06:51,923
...it seems like an awful waste of space.

71
00:07:08,939 --> 00:07:11,274
CQ, CQ.

72
00:07:11,442 --> 00:07:13,776
CQ, this is W-9 GFO.

73
00:07:13,985 --> 00:07:17,112
Repeat. This is W-9 GFO. Come back?

74
00:07:18,658 --> 00:07:22,035
CQ, this is W-9 GFO. Come back?

75
00:07:24,663 --> 00:07:27,122
I'm gonna need a bigger antenna.

76
00:07:53,692 --> 00:07:55,442
MAN:
What do you think, Doctor Arroway?

77
00:07:55,610 --> 00:07:57,612
Isn't she a beauty?

78
00:08:01,158 --> 00:08:02,283
It'll do.

79
00:08:02,492 --> 00:08:04,451
FISHER:
The village is five miles away.

80
00:08:04,661 --> 00:08:09,249
There's a general store in the cantina.
They can order anything from San Juan.

81
00:08:09,416 --> 00:08:11,000
ELLIE:
And when can I get some dish time?

82
00:08:11,168 --> 00:08:14,545
FISHER: Dr. Clark said you wouldn't
be able to wait. Your first shift is tonight.

83
00:08:14,713 --> 00:08:15,838
ELLIE:
All right.

84
00:09:01,051 --> 00:09:03,384
[STATIC BUZZING OVER RADIO]

85
00:09:10,976 --> 00:09:12,477
Go back.

86
00:09:13,897 --> 00:09:16,981
Try back a little bit.
You had something there.

87
00:09:17,149 --> 00:09:18,192
[WHIRRING ON RADIO]

88
00:09:18,360 --> 00:09:19,442
There.

89
00:09:19,610 --> 00:09:22,696
- Right there?
- You hear it? Right there, that's it.

90
00:09:22,864 --> 00:09:26,741
ELLIE: All right, 1221.46.
That's well within the L band.

91
00:09:26,909 --> 00:09:29,995
- Check off-axis.
- Uh-huh. On it.

92
00:09:31,081 --> 00:09:33,749
It's not in the neighborhood.

93
00:09:39,380 --> 00:09:41,048
Ah.

94
00:09:42,216 --> 00:09:46,094
Here it is. J-1741 plus 2748.

95
00:09:46,260 --> 00:09:49,931
Catalogued November 4, 1982. Pulsar.

96
00:09:50,765 --> 00:09:55,269
Well, I don't know, it must've been...
The glitch in the timing is what threw me.

97
00:09:55,437 --> 00:09:57,145
Must've been a starquake.

98
00:09:57,313 --> 00:09:58,355
[WHIRRING STOPS]

99
00:09:58,524 --> 00:10:02,360
I think it's great that you listen.
Most people don't do that anymore.

100
00:10:02,528 --> 00:10:05,404
It's just an old habit.
You know, it makes it feel more real.

101
00:10:05,572 --> 00:10:08,448
- Ellie.
- Kent. Kent Clark.

102
00:10:09,493 --> 00:10:10,618
Hey.

103
00:10:10,785 --> 00:10:15,081
They said you've been up at Owens Valley
working under Drumlin.

104
00:10:15,249 --> 00:10:16,832
How did you like him?

105
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:18,292
[ELLIE SIGHS]

106
00:10:19,794 --> 00:10:24,131
That much? And about what I'd expect
after what he had to say about you.

107
00:10:24,298 --> 00:10:26,299
What was that?

108
00:10:26,467 --> 00:10:29,595
That you are brilliant, driven...

109
00:10:29,763 --> 00:10:32,764
...a major pain in the ass,
and obsessed with a field of study...

110
00:10:32,932 --> 00:10:36,101
...that he considers tantamount
to professional suicide.

111
00:10:37,019 --> 00:10:40,148
- Anything else?
- Those were the highlights.

112
00:10:40,315 --> 00:10:42,607
Davio, Dr. Vernon. Dr. Arroway.

113
00:10:42,775 --> 00:10:44,235
ELLIE: Hey. Hi there.
- How you doing?

114
00:10:44,403 --> 00:10:48,990
And I believe you've already met our
tireless research assistant, Mr. Fisher...

115
00:10:49,158 --> 00:10:51,951
- Here, I need you to sign...
...as well as his cologne.

116
00:10:52,119 --> 00:10:54,703
Brook's looking at the black hole
at the center of M-87.

117
00:10:54,871 --> 00:10:58,624
Eli's studying Markarian 541,
a major gamma-ray source.

118
00:10:58,792 --> 00:11:03,837
And Dr. Arroway will be spending her
precious telescope time listening for, um...

119
00:11:04,214 --> 00:11:06,214
Listening for...

120
00:11:06,381 --> 00:11:08,174
Little green men.

121
00:11:15,932 --> 00:11:19,519
One down, a couple billion to go.

122
00:11:22,273 --> 00:11:23,940
[SPEAKING IN SPANISH]

123
00:11:36,203 --> 00:11:38,163
Arecibo, right?

124
00:11:39,331 --> 00:11:40,499
Does it show?

125
00:11:41,125 --> 00:11:42,375
Yeah.

126
00:11:42,543 --> 00:11:44,836
- Cracker Jack?
- No, thanks.

127
00:11:45,004 --> 00:11:46,546
- Mind if I sit down?
- Sure.

128
00:11:48,216 --> 00:11:52,219
I hear the locals, they call it El Radar.

129
00:11:52,385 --> 00:11:55,221
Convinced it has
some dark military purpose.

130
00:11:55,389 --> 00:11:56,807
I think we're pretty harmless.

131
00:11:58,267 --> 00:11:59,392
Palmer Joss.

132
00:12:00,227 --> 00:12:02,687
- Ellie Arroway.
- Nice to meet you, Ellie.

133
00:12:03,898 --> 00:12:06,857
What are you studying up there?

134
00:12:08,528 --> 00:12:09,903
The usual.

135
00:12:10,071 --> 00:12:13,114
You know. Nebulae, quasars, pulsars,
stuff like that.

136
00:12:13,282 --> 00:12:15,866
What are you...? What are you writing?

137
00:12:16,034 --> 00:12:20,413
The usual. Nouns, adverbs,
adjective here and there.

138
00:12:21,749 --> 00:12:23,250
I work on a project called SETI.

139
00:12:24,043 --> 00:12:26,086
Search for Extraterrestrial Intelligence?

140
00:12:26,754 --> 00:12:30,338
Wow. Man, that is out there.

141
00:12:31,131 --> 00:12:32,966
Wait, are you a student or something?

142
00:12:33,134 --> 00:12:36,427
Mm-mm. I'm a writer. I'm writing a book.

143
00:12:36,596 --> 00:12:41,267
Down here doing research about how
technology affects Third World cultures.

144
00:12:41,433 --> 00:12:44,269
I'm also looking for this guy
David Drumlin.

145
00:12:44,437 --> 00:12:48,899
He's the new head of the National Science
Foundation. I'm trying to get an interview.

146
00:12:49,775 --> 00:12:52,778
- I take it you know him?
- Mm-hm.

147
00:12:52,946 --> 00:12:54,904
You could say that.

148
00:12:55,740 --> 00:12:59,409
SETI, man. That's fringe.

149
00:12:59,577 --> 00:13:01,120
I've crossed paths with this guy.

150
00:13:01,288 --> 00:13:03,956
Something like that
must really chap his ass, huh?

151
00:13:06,918 --> 00:13:08,293
Compass.

152
00:13:09,962 --> 00:13:11,547
For you, EI.

153
00:13:16,135 --> 00:13:17,927
You better keep this.

154
00:13:18,804 --> 00:13:20,931
Might save your life someday.

155
00:13:25,102 --> 00:13:26,895
Will you have dinner with me tonight?

156
00:13:28,440 --> 00:13:29,773
I...

157
00:13:29,941 --> 00:13:33,568
I don't make a very good research subject.
I'm just not very quotable.

158
00:13:33,736 --> 00:13:37,489
No quotes. No quotes. Scout's honor.
Just a good meal, good company.

159
00:13:38,325 --> 00:13:40,158
I gotta go.

160
00:13:43,370 --> 00:13:45,496
But, uh...

161
00:13:48,793 --> 00:13:51,128
Drumlirs coming in this Tuesday.

162
00:13:59,510 --> 00:14:03,389
Now I remember why I took that desk job.

163
00:14:04,390 --> 00:14:06,934
- Dr. Drumlin, how are you?
- Dr. Drumlin.

164
00:14:07,894 --> 00:14:09,979
Glad you could make it, David.

165
00:14:10,438 --> 00:14:13,691
If I'd known it was gonna take
three planes, I might've reconsidered.

166
00:14:13,859 --> 00:14:15,234
How is that new office?

167
00:14:15,402 --> 00:14:19,989
I'm still settling in. They already wanna take
half my budget and give it to the Pentagon.

168
00:14:20,157 --> 00:14:23,033
Ellie. Still waiting for E.T. To call?

169
00:14:23,201 --> 00:14:27,205
- Well, I understand we're having a little...
- Good to see you too.

170
00:14:27,373 --> 00:14:28,373
Asshole.

171
00:14:28,539 --> 00:14:30,875
Uh-oh. Looks like
it's gonna be a long night.

172
00:14:31,043 --> 00:14:35,504
Science must first be accountable to the
people who are paying for it, the taxpayers.

173
00:14:35,673 --> 00:14:39,049
We need to stop wasting money
on pie-in-the-sky abstractions...

174
00:14:39,217 --> 00:14:42,177
...and start spending it on practical,
measurable ways...

175
00:14:42,346 --> 00:14:45,222
...to improve the lives of the people
who are footing the bill.

176
00:14:45,390 --> 00:14:48,518
Not unlike my L-band,
globular-clusters work.

177
00:14:48,686 --> 00:14:51,729
Wait, you're saying you wanna do away
with all pure research now?

178
00:14:51,897 --> 00:14:55,232
What's wrong with science being practical?
Even profitable?

179
00:14:55,442 --> 00:14:59,278
Nothing, as long as your motive
is the search for truth.

180
00:14:59,446 --> 00:15:02,572
Which is exactly what
the pursuit of science is.

181
00:15:04,118 --> 00:15:05,951
That's a rather interesting position...

182
00:15:06,120 --> 00:15:09,788
...coming from a man on a crusade
against the evils of technology...

183
00:15:09,956 --> 00:15:11,039
...Father Joss.

184
00:15:11,708 --> 00:15:14,085
PALMER:
I'm not against technology, doctor.

185
00:15:14,253 --> 00:15:18,504
I'm against the men who deify it
at the expense of human truth.

186
00:15:22,342 --> 00:15:25,553
Kent, I've been meaning to have
a word with you. Over here, please.

187
00:15:25,721 --> 00:15:27,596
KENT:
Yeah, I'll just...

188
00:15:31,601 --> 00:15:34,730
I think that hurt my chances
with that interview. What do you think?

189
00:15:35,355 --> 00:15:37,190
You're a priest?

190
00:15:38,692 --> 00:15:39,942
No, not really.

191
00:15:40,610 --> 00:15:43,697
I got my Masters in Divinity...

192
00:15:43,865 --> 00:15:47,451
...then dropped out of seminary to
do some secular humanitarian work...

193
00:15:47,618 --> 00:15:50,120
...coordinating efforts
for Third World churches.

194
00:15:50,705 --> 00:15:53,373
I couldn't live with
the whole celibacy thing.

195
00:15:55,751 --> 00:15:57,126
You could...

196
00:15:57,294 --> 00:15:59,879
You could call me a man of the cloth...

197
00:16:00,715 --> 00:16:02,298
...without the cloth.

198
00:16:05,635 --> 00:16:07,303
You wanna get out of here?

199
00:16:09,222 --> 00:16:12,725
All right, you see that sort of large,
W-shaped constellation right there?

200
00:16:12,894 --> 00:16:14,351
That's Cassiopeia.

201
00:16:14,519 --> 00:16:19,066
And Cassiopeia A gives off
a whole lot of radio signals.

202
00:16:19,232 --> 00:16:23,736
I actually listen to them a lot.
It's a remnant of a supernova.

203
00:16:24,447 --> 00:16:27,323
When did you know
you wanted to be an astronomer?

204
00:16:27,825 --> 00:16:29,283
Well, when I...

205
00:16:29,451 --> 00:16:33,288
When I was about 8 years old,
I was watching the sunset...

206
00:16:33,456 --> 00:16:36,832
...and I asked my dad,
"What's that bright star over there?"

207
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:39,668
Dad, what's that star there?

208
00:16:40,253 --> 00:16:43,338
And he said that it wasrt
really a star at all. It was actually...

209
00:16:43,506 --> 00:16:45,173
That's not a star, it's a planet.

210
00:16:45,341 --> 00:16:46,966
- A whole planet called Venus...

211
00:16:47,134 --> 00:16:49,135
That's the planet Venus.

212
00:16:51,472 --> 00:16:55,433
- Which should be over there soon.

213
00:16:55,601 --> 00:16:58,312
He said,
"You know why they called it Venus?

214
00:16:58,480 --> 00:17:01,774
Because they thought
it was so beautiful and glowing.

215
00:17:01,942 --> 00:17:04,026
But what they didn't know...

216
00:17:04,193 --> 00:17:06,820
...is that it's filled with...

217
00:17:08,030 --> 00:17:11,741
...deadly gases and sulfuric acid rain."

218
00:17:12,786 --> 00:17:16,997
"Wow," I thought,
"This is it! I'm hooked."

219
00:17:18,541 --> 00:17:22,545
You know, there are four hundred billion
stars out there...

220
00:17:22,711 --> 00:17:24,963
...just in our galaxy alone.

221
00:17:25,298 --> 00:17:29,218
If only one out of a million
of those had planets...

222
00:17:29,385 --> 00:17:32,555
...all right, and ifjust one
out of a million of those had life...

223
00:17:32,721 --> 00:17:37,351
...and ifjust one out of a million
of those had intelligent life...

224
00:17:37,644 --> 00:17:42,647
...there would be literally millions
of civilizations out there.

225
00:17:44,067 --> 00:17:46,152
Well, if there wasrt...

226
00:17:46,569 --> 00:17:49,070
...it'd be an awful waste of space.

227
00:17:54,661 --> 00:17:56,412
Amen.

228
00:18:04,752 --> 00:18:09,757
PALMER: So I was lying there,
just looking at the sky.

229
00:18:12,678 --> 00:18:16,513
And then I felt something. I don't know, I...

230
00:18:17,016 --> 00:18:19,893
All I know is that I wasrt alone.

231
00:18:20,059 --> 00:18:24,980
And for the first time in my life
I wasrt scared of nothing, you know?

232
00:18:25,148 --> 00:18:27,107
Not even dying.

233
00:18:32,448 --> 00:18:34,490
It was God.

234
00:18:36,951 --> 00:18:39,287
And there's no chance that...

235
00:18:39,454 --> 00:18:43,708
...you had this experience because
some part of you needed to have it?

236
00:18:44,960 --> 00:18:48,462
I mean, I'm a reasonably intelligent guy,
but this...

237
00:18:51,299 --> 00:18:55,302
No, this... No, my intellect,
it couldn't even touch this.

238
00:18:55,471 --> 00:18:56,511
No.

239
00:18:58,973 --> 00:19:01,558
I've been to Sunday school a few times.

240
00:19:02,978 --> 00:19:04,729
Uh-huh. And?

241
00:19:04,896 --> 00:19:10,151
Well, I just kept asking all these
really annoying questions like:

242
00:19:10,318 --> 00:19:13,278
"All right, then where did Mrs. Cain
come from?"

243
00:19:14,573 --> 00:19:17,157
And pretty soon they called my dad
and they asked him...

244
00:19:17,326 --> 00:19:20,077
...if he wouldn't mind just
keeping me home from now on.

245
00:19:20,246 --> 00:19:22,288
Your dad...

246
00:19:23,249 --> 00:19:26,459
- Is it this guy?
- Yeah.

247
00:19:28,336 --> 00:19:30,796
You're close to him, aren't you?

248
00:19:31,673 --> 00:19:35,133
Yeah, I was.
He died when I was 9 years old.

249
00:19:37,010 --> 00:19:39,011
I never got to know my mother.

250
00:19:40,597 --> 00:19:41,932
I'm sorry.

251
00:19:46,436 --> 00:19:48,355
That's gotta be tough.

252
00:19:50,566 --> 00:19:52,233
Yeah.

253
00:19:52,859 --> 00:19:54,861
Being alone.

254
00:20:03,371 --> 00:20:04,621
What do you say...

255
00:20:04,830 --> 00:20:08,333
...we pack a picnic tomorrow morning
and hike up to old Mount Arecibo?

256
00:20:09,210 --> 00:20:12,211
I don't think I can. I gotta work.

257
00:20:14,007 --> 00:20:17,634
All right, how about dinner, then,
tomorrow night? I know a great dive.

258
00:20:17,801 --> 00:20:19,760
I don't think so.

259
00:20:24,057 --> 00:20:27,227
- Ellie, did I miss something?
- Huh?

260
00:20:28,354 --> 00:20:31,565
No. Shit, I'm late.

261
00:20:32,525 --> 00:20:36,111
I told Kent that I'd be there at 10:30.

262
00:20:38,072 --> 00:20:39,865
You know, I'm not trying to push you.

263
00:20:40,074 --> 00:20:42,491
No, no. I've wanted to look at
this sector for weeks.

264
00:20:42,660 --> 00:20:47,913
Just hang out and sleep in.
And there's a bunch of food in the fridge.

265
00:20:48,082 --> 00:20:49,249
Okay?

266
00:20:49,416 --> 00:20:51,250
How can I reach you?

267
00:20:51,917 --> 00:20:54,420
Just leave your number. I'll call you.

268
00:21:15,901 --> 00:21:16,942
YOUNG ELLIE:
Dad!

269
00:21:18,987 --> 00:21:21,989
Dad, it's starting, you're gonna miss it.

270
00:21:25,117 --> 00:21:27,411
Dad, there's another one. Hurry up.

271
00:21:27,578 --> 00:21:29,954
TED:
In a minute, Sparks. I'm almost done.

272
00:21:30,123 --> 00:21:32,958
There's another one.
Come on, hurry up, Dad!

273
00:21:35,002 --> 00:21:37,003
[CLATTERING]

274
00:21:38,298 --> 00:21:52,894
Dad?

275
00:22:03,030 --> 00:22:04,115
Daddy?

276
00:22:17,086 --> 00:22:26,510
Dad.

277
00:22:28,513 --> 00:22:30,432
I'll get the medicine.

278
00:23:46,007 --> 00:23:47,673
Ellie.

279
00:23:49,259 --> 00:23:51,929
I know it's hard to understand this now...

280
00:23:52,931 --> 00:23:57,433
...but we aren't always meant to know
why things happen the way they do.

281
00:23:57,977 --> 00:24:02,314
Sometimes we just have to accept it
as God's will.

282
00:24:04,275 --> 00:24:07,944
I should have kept some medicine
in the downstairs bathroom.

283
00:24:08,112 --> 00:24:10,655
Then I could've gotten to it sooner.

284
00:24:26,631 --> 00:24:29,090
[CHATTERING]

285
00:24:36,182 --> 00:24:37,848
YOUNG ELLIE:
CQ...

286
00:24:38,684 --> 00:24:41,979
...this is W-9 GFO. Do you copy?

287
00:24:45,148 --> 00:24:47,817
Dad, this is Ellie. Come back.

288
00:24:50,989 --> 00:24:53,030
This is Eleanor Arroway...

289
00:24:53,199 --> 00:24:56,785
...transmitting on 14.2 megahertz.

290
00:24:59,288 --> 00:25:00,872
Dad.

291
00:25:02,915 --> 00:25:04,416
Are you there?

292
00:25:06,545 --> 00:25:08,003
Come back.

293
00:25:10,923 --> 00:25:12,340
Dad.

294
00:25:14,720 --> 00:25:16,178
Are you there?

295
00:25:17,221 --> 00:25:18,722
Dad, this is Ellie.

296
00:25:27,732 --> 00:25:30,233
[BEEPING]

297
00:25:48,086 --> 00:25:50,046
[DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES]

298
00:25:50,212 --> 00:25:51,505
Ellie.

299
00:25:51,673 --> 00:25:55,050
Hi, Kent. What are you doing
up so early, huh?

300
00:25:55,719 --> 00:25:57,052
I was thinking...

301
00:25:57,762 --> 00:25:59,305
...we'd make a pretty good team.

302
00:25:59,472 --> 00:26:00,513
What?

303
00:26:00,682 --> 00:26:04,184
We could put together
a kick-ass ad-hoc SETI program.

304
00:26:04,394 --> 00:26:06,604
You know the Very Large Array
in New Mexico?

305
00:26:06,771 --> 00:26:09,230
It would be a dynamite place
to do serious SETI...

306
00:26:09,398 --> 00:26:12,067
What are you talking about, Kent?

307
00:26:13,528 --> 00:26:15,403
Drumlin pulled the plug.

308
00:26:16,030 --> 00:26:17,155
We're homeless.

309
00:26:27,750 --> 00:26:29,541
Hey, watch it.

310
00:26:31,295 --> 00:26:33,212
ELLIE:
Is it true, huh? Did you pull the plug?

311
00:26:33,381 --> 00:26:35,757
You can't see it now,
but I'm doing you a favor.

312
00:26:35,924 --> 00:26:40,095
You are far too promising a scientist
to be wasting your gifts on this nonsense.

313
00:26:40,261 --> 00:26:42,262
Look, I don't consider what could be...

314
00:26:42,472 --> 00:26:45,474
...the most important discovery
of the human race nonsense, okay?

315
00:26:45,643 --> 00:26:47,059
There's 400 billion stars...

316
00:26:47,228 --> 00:26:50,105
And two probabilities.
One, there is intelligent life...

317
00:26:50,314 --> 00:26:53,316
...but it's so far away you'll
never contact it in your lifetime.

318
00:26:53,483 --> 00:26:55,693
- And two!
- You're making a decision...

319
00:26:55,861 --> 00:27:00,280
There's nothing but noble gases and carbon
compounds and you're wasting your time.

320
00:27:00,449 --> 00:27:03,535
In the meantime, you won't be published,
won't be taken seriously.

321
00:27:03,702 --> 00:27:05,412
And your career will be over.

322
00:27:05,578 --> 00:27:08,957
So what? It's my life.

323
00:27:45,994 --> 00:27:48,872
Hey, Kent. You were right.

324
00:27:49,038 --> 00:27:52,750
Screw Drumlin. We're gonna raise
the money. We're going to New Mexico.

325
00:27:52,916 --> 00:27:55,461
KENT: Chicago has all the stuff,
but let me know how it goes.

326
00:27:55,627 --> 00:27:58,505
I've got some more corporate stops
on the East Coast for you.

327
00:27:58,673 --> 00:28:01,842
Hey, Fish, did that investor from Houston
ever get back to us?

328
00:28:02,009 --> 00:28:04,010
FISHER:
I'm gonna hit him up on my way to L.A.

329
00:28:04,220 --> 00:28:06,346
ELLIE: Try begging for some of that
Hollywood money.

330
00:28:06,556 --> 00:28:10,142
Why not? They've been making money
off of aliens for years, right?

331
00:28:10,309 --> 00:28:13,144
- Begging is good for the soul.
- We'll see about that.

332
00:28:13,313 --> 00:28:14,980
- Just do me a favor.
- Yeah.

333
00:28:15,147 --> 00:28:17,941
Try not to be too confrontational.

334
00:28:18,108 --> 00:28:20,568
Huh? Confrontational? Me?
What do you mean?

335
00:28:20,737 --> 00:28:22,362
I'm gonna see if I left anything.

336
00:28:55,730 --> 00:28:59,566
ELLIE: This is a unique time in our history,
in the history of any civilization.

337
00:28:59,733 --> 00:29:02,528
It's the moment
of the acquisition of technology.

338
00:29:02,737 --> 00:29:05,571
That's the moment
where contact becomes possible.

339
00:29:06,281 --> 00:29:11,118
The Very Large Array in New Mexico
is the key to our chances for success.

340
00:29:11,287 --> 00:29:13,538
With its 27 linked radio telescopes...

341
00:29:13,704 --> 00:29:17,083
...we can search more accurately
than at any other conventional facility.

342
00:29:17,250 --> 00:29:22,421
Now, we've gotten approval to buy
the telescope time from the government.

343
00:29:22,923 --> 00:29:25,090
Now all we really need is the money.

344
00:29:25,884 --> 00:29:27,884
A nice presentation, doctor.

345
00:29:28,595 --> 00:29:33,098
But while our foundation arm has a mandate
to support experimental programs...

346
00:29:33,267 --> 00:29:37,228
...we must confess that
your proposal seems less like science...

347
00:29:37,395 --> 00:29:39,105
...and more like science fiction.

348
00:29:41,607 --> 00:29:43,067
Science fiction.

349
00:29:46,488 --> 00:29:48,280
You're right.

350
00:29:48,740 --> 00:29:50,324
It's crazy.

351
00:29:51,117 --> 00:29:54,077
In fact, it's even worse than that: Nuts.

352
00:29:55,622 --> 00:29:57,123
You wanna hear something nutty?

353
00:29:57,290 --> 00:29:59,959
A couple guys wanted to build
something called an airplane.

354
00:30:00,126 --> 00:30:03,296
You get people to go in it and fly like birds.
Ridiculous, right?

355
00:30:03,462 --> 00:30:05,423
Or what about
breaking the sound barrier...

356
00:30:05,590 --> 00:30:09,218
...or rockets to the moon,
or atomic energy or a mission to Mars?

357
00:30:09,428 --> 00:30:11,261
Science fiction, right?

358
00:30:11,430 --> 00:30:12,555
Look.

359
00:30:12,722 --> 00:30:16,976
All I'm asking is for you to
just have the tiniest bit of vision.

360
00:30:17,144 --> 00:30:20,730
You know, to just step back for one minute
and look at the big picture.

361
00:30:20,897 --> 00:30:22,355
To take a chance on something...

362
00:30:22,523 --> 00:30:26,152
...which might end up being
the most profoundly impactful moment...

363
00:30:26,319 --> 00:30:30,489
...for humanity, for the history of history.

364
00:30:33,701 --> 00:30:35,243
I'm sorry.

365
00:30:36,371 --> 00:30:37,996
I just spent the last 13 months...

366
00:30:38,663 --> 00:30:42,000
...coming into rooms like this
and talking to people like you.

367
00:30:42,417 --> 00:30:45,127
The truth is, you're my last chance, so...

368
00:30:45,296 --> 00:30:46,755
I'm sorry I wasted your time.

369
00:30:46,923 --> 00:30:48,213
Doctor.

370
00:30:48,382 --> 00:30:58,849
Yes, sir.

371
00:31:01,938 --> 00:31:03,145
You have your money.

372
00:31:06,192 --> 00:31:10,987
Thank you.

373
00:31:39,349 --> 00:31:41,851
[MOTOR HUMMING]

374
00:31:57,535 --> 00:32:01,577
MAN:
Oh! Perfect cast. Come on, fishy.

375
00:32:01,746 --> 00:32:05,415
Frank, look at the size
of that son of a bitch!

376
00:32:17,846 --> 00:32:19,930
Welcome back, Dr. C.

377
00:32:20,097 --> 00:32:21,597
How'd it go?

378
00:32:22,267 --> 00:32:25,519
- How was the trip?
- I've had better.

379
00:32:26,020 --> 00:32:29,105
Drumlin. What is this?
This his personal vendetta now?

380
00:32:29,273 --> 00:32:33,192
It's not just Drumlin. There's been enormous
pressure from other scientists as well.

381
00:32:33,361 --> 00:32:36,613
It doesn't matter anyway,
Hadders funding us for another two years.

382
00:32:36,780 --> 00:32:39,950
Uh... These are government-owned
telescopes, they can lease to whomever.

383
00:32:40,117 --> 00:32:43,912
And they don't want the high priestess
of the desert using them anymore.

384
00:32:44,748 --> 00:32:45,788
What?

385
00:32:45,957 --> 00:32:49,292
Staring at static on TV for hours,
listening to washing machines.

386
00:32:49,461 --> 00:32:51,836
Did you really think these stories
wouldn't get out?

387
00:32:52,005 --> 00:32:55,758
- I was looking for patterns in the chaos.
- Doesrt matter, we're a joke to them.

388
00:32:55,924 --> 00:32:57,468
They want us out.

389
00:32:58,927 --> 00:33:02,263
We've got three months
until the paperwork goes through.

390
00:33:04,976 --> 00:33:08,144
Fine. I'll start looking for other funding.
I'll just start...

391
00:33:08,313 --> 00:33:12,816
Could you face reality, please?
Just this once, Ellie. We lost.

392
00:33:12,983 --> 00:33:14,651
It's over.

393
00:33:20,991 --> 00:33:22,659
Fine.

394
00:33:22,826 --> 00:33:24,826
But I'm not stopping.

395
00:33:24,994 --> 00:33:27,997
If I have to go it alone, I'll go it alone.
I've done it before.

396
00:34:17,755 --> 00:34:21,509
My guest tonight is author
and theologian Palmer Joss.

397
00:34:21,677 --> 00:34:26,681
He's become a spiritual counselor of sorts
and a recent fixture at the White House.

398
00:34:26,849 --> 00:34:29,809
"God's Diplomat,"
according to The New York Times.

399
00:34:30,018 --> 00:34:33,688
His latest book, Losing Faith,
is currently number one...

400
00:34:33,896 --> 00:34:36,231
...on that publicatiors bestseller list.

401
00:34:36,400 --> 00:34:37,900
Thanks for being with us, Palmer.

402
00:34:38,068 --> 00:34:40,862
You have had quite a ride
this last couple of years.

403
00:34:41,028 --> 00:34:43,489
Yeah, I sure have, Larry.

404
00:34:43,657 --> 00:34:46,159
You know, Fish, I was thinking.

405
00:34:46,326 --> 00:34:50,661
Who would make the best astronomers?
I mean, think about it.

406
00:34:50,829 --> 00:34:56,835
Who has the perfect synthesis
of career and lifestyle?

407
00:34:57,003 --> 00:34:59,920
- I give.
- Vampires!

408
00:35:00,088 --> 00:35:02,507
Are you anti-technology?
Are you anti-science?

409
00:35:02,675 --> 00:35:04,675
PALMER:
No, not at all.

410
00:35:04,844 --> 00:35:07,721
The question that I'm asking is this:

411
00:35:08,389 --> 00:35:11,099
Are we happier as a human race?

412
00:35:11,266 --> 00:35:16,188
Is the world fundamentally a better place
because of science and technology?

413
00:35:16,898 --> 00:35:19,356
We shop at home, we surf the Web...

414
00:35:19,567 --> 00:35:22,360
...but at the same time we feel emptier...

415
00:35:22,527 --> 00:35:27,364
...and more cut off from each other
than at any other time in human history.

416
00:35:27,532 --> 00:35:30,202
I mean, we're becoming
a synthesized society...

417
00:35:30,369 --> 00:35:33,704
...in a great, big hurry
to get to the next...

418
00:35:47,094 --> 00:35:50,597
I think it's because we're looking
for the meaning. What is the meaning?

419
00:35:50,764 --> 00:35:53,474
We have mindless jobs,
we take frantic vacations.

420
00:35:53,893 --> 00:35:56,894
Deficit finance trips to the mall
to buy more things...

421
00:35:57,103 --> 00:36:00,773
...that we think are gonna fill
these holes in our lives.

422
00:36:00,942 --> 00:36:03,485
Is it any wonder that we've lost
our sense of direction?

423
00:36:19,208 --> 00:36:23,963
[BUZZING AND PULSING]

424
00:36:44,358 --> 00:36:46,025
Holy shit.

425
00:36:59,373 --> 00:37:01,375
[ENGINE STARTS]

426
00:37:04,336 --> 00:37:10,384
Right ascension,
18 hours, 36 minutes, 56.2 seconds.

427
00:37:10,552 --> 00:37:15,556
Declination, plus 36 degrees,
46 minutes...

428
00:37:15,724 --> 00:37:18,891
...56.2 seconds!

429
00:37:20,561 --> 00:37:22,061
Confirm!

430
00:37:22,230 --> 00:37:28,152
Right ascension, 18 hours, 36 minutes,
56.2 seconds!

431
00:37:28,320 --> 00:37:31,155
Hey, is anybody awake in there?
I'm moving the array!

432
00:37:32,239 --> 00:37:35,034
- Confirm!
- Boss has a bogey!

433
00:37:35,242 --> 00:37:40,371
Right ascension, 18 hours,
36 minutes, 56.2 seconds.

434
00:37:40,539 --> 00:37:42,789
- Fish!
- We're on it.

435
00:37:42,958 --> 00:37:47,295
Plus 36 hours,
47 minutes and 1 second.

436
00:37:47,463 --> 00:37:51,215
Strong possible pulse chain
on Sub-Array 4.

437
00:37:51,425 --> 00:37:54,760
I'm moving the rest of them now.
I need you to confirm the coordinates.

438
00:37:54,927 --> 00:37:56,929
Check the status of the array.

439
00:37:57,097 --> 00:38:00,974
- She's doing all the dishes.
- All systems nominal.

440
00:38:05,606 --> 00:38:07,190
Hello.

441
00:38:07,940 --> 00:38:09,692
I need a full systems check.

442
00:38:09,860 --> 00:38:12,695
Coordinates confirmed.
Willie's checking the system now.

443
00:38:12,862 --> 00:38:15,864
Stay on top of the systems diagnostics.

444
00:38:16,032 --> 00:38:17,742
Check the reference point offsets.

445
00:38:17,951 --> 00:38:21,954
And I want you off-axis on 27
the second we get there.

446
00:38:22,121 --> 00:38:24,623
And tell Willie to break out the big boy.

447
00:38:26,210 --> 00:38:28,543
Copy that. Willie...

448
00:38:28,711 --> 00:38:29,961
Yeah. Go, Ellie.

449
00:38:30,130 --> 00:38:33,423
I can hear can it on the headphones.
We gotta be sure about this.

450
00:38:33,592 --> 00:38:36,302
Give me another array status.

451
00:38:37,721 --> 00:38:40,639
Her four are online,
the rest are tracking in.

452
00:38:40,807 --> 00:38:43,559
FISHER: Your four are online,
the rest are tracking in.

453
00:38:43,726 --> 00:38:46,103
But there's a bad drive on 16.

454
00:38:46,313 --> 00:38:48,815
Your four are online,
the rest are tracking in...

455
00:38:48,981 --> 00:38:51,818
...but there's a bad drive on 16.
Copy that?

456
00:38:53,070 --> 00:38:55,362
What do you want me to do
about the source queue?

457
00:38:55,530 --> 00:38:57,614
Look, forget about it and hold the queue.

458
00:38:57,782 --> 00:39:01,952
Go get ready to set the target frequency
to manual the second we're aligned.

459
00:39:02,161 --> 00:39:06,498
Do you copy? I want you to go
off-axis on 27 the second we're there.

460
00:39:06,748 --> 00:39:09,583
And leave the LO frequency where it is.

461
00:39:09,751 --> 00:39:13,045
Stay on it, Fish, don't let it get away.
If you lose it, scan the band.

462
00:39:13,213 --> 00:39:16,507
Run every frequency you can think of.

463
00:39:21,097 --> 00:39:22,806
How you doing?

464
00:39:27,018 --> 00:39:28,144
Talk to me, guys.

465
00:39:28,353 --> 00:39:32,190
Partially polarized set of moving pulses,
amplitude modulated.

466
00:39:32,358 --> 00:39:36,027
We're locked. Systems check out, signal
across the board. What's the frequency?

467
00:39:36,195 --> 00:39:39,239
4.46, 23 gigahertz.

468
00:39:40,615 --> 00:39:43,869
Hydrogen times pi. Told you.

469
00:39:44,036 --> 00:39:45,829
Strong sucker too.

470
00:39:45,996 --> 00:39:48,331
I got it! I got it, I got it!
I'm patched in.

471
00:39:49,041 --> 00:39:50,708
ELLIE:
All right, let me hear it.

472
00:39:53,838 --> 00:39:55,588
[PULSING]

473
00:39:55,755 --> 00:39:57,215
Listen to that.

474
00:39:59,469 --> 00:40:01,719
Make me a liar, Fish.

475
00:40:01,887 --> 00:40:04,556
It could be AWACS out of Kirtland
jamming us.

476
00:40:04,724 --> 00:40:06,099
But I'm doubting it.

477
00:40:06,266 --> 00:40:08,893
All right, let's see
if F.U.D.D.'s reading it too.

478
00:40:09,728 --> 00:40:13,063
Willie, patch it back
and give me the off-axis.

479
00:40:13,231 --> 00:40:14,900
- Are we recording?
- Never stopped.

480
00:40:16,985 --> 00:40:18,277
Thank you, Elmer.

481
00:40:18,487 --> 00:40:20,405
AWACS status is negative.

482
00:40:20,572 --> 00:40:23,407
- White Sands?
- On this frequency? No.

483
00:40:23,574 --> 00:40:25,074
I'm gonna punch up the darks.

